<font color="#FF0000">VIETNAM</font><br>
<tt>Tue Nov 26 15:44:18 US/Eastern 1996
</tt><p>
I am 27 years old.  My father was packed and ready to be shipped over to Vietnam with the Marines when the war ended.  He lost many very close friends to the war, and like many, he was torn between patriotic duty and personal beliefs.  One way he dealt with this was by adopting a refugee family.  Hoa, Thuy and their baby Jimmy (named after my father) lived with us in our home in Maitland, Florida for 2 years.  It was a wonderful experience for my brother and me as well as an incredible chance to heal for parents.  It opened our eyes to another culture and forced us all to reckon with prejudices.  This was a struggling family just like ours, and they had very mixed emotions about leaving homeland, family and friends forever.  Thuy would spend hours showing me photos of her sister and teaching me the name of every object in the pictures.  To this day I have quite a large Vietnamese vocabulary, and I hope desperately to be able to visit one day.<br><br>
Christine Carey<br>
Dallas, Texas
